Text.Value: The foundry is in the Lower City, down by the docks. Beautiful building, belching smoke into the sky day and night.
The Gondians are making weapons for a tyrant - that makes them the enemy.
They'll find you, and they'll kill you.
Fine. You want to try flapping your gums in the belly of the beast, be my guest.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: dismissive gesture, he's disgusted with us and our attempts to befriend the enemy

Text.Value: But I believe in second chances. When you come crawling back here - and you will - we can talk.
I'm sneaky - I'll keep clear of them.
The Gondians are ingenious. But we're more than equal to them - there's nothing they can build that the Ironhands can't tear down.
This is your fight - not mine.
And the fucking Gondians are to blame for all of it.
I don't have the bomb anymore.
The Gondians are just inventors. You can't blame them for Gortash's actions.
A runepowder bomb - first of its kind. Fifty wizards high on the Weave couldn't summon this kind of firepower.
Well, maybe you can blame them for that.
The Steel Watch. They're a threat to you, me - and every man, woman and child in the city.
I'm running out of patience. Friend.
Gortash is a dead man - I have reasons of my own for taking him down.
Getting inside won't be easy, but when you do, place the bomb at the heart of the facility, get yourself back to street level.
Whatever brought you to the city, you won't get anywhere while the Gondians' metal monsters are patrolling the streets.
Maybe I can help.
This plan seems a bit loud for my liking. Messy, too.
No.
Find another way to shut down that foundry, or you might as well slip your head in a noose right now. Gortash will string us all up.
The Gondians picked their side the minute they took orders from Gortash.
The Gondians made a choice. They will suffer the consequences.
Killing innocents won't right this wrong, Wulbren.
That's what I've been saying! There may yet be a peaceful solution.
Yes - but not using your methods.
Give me the bomb. I'll make sure nobody survives - guard, Gondian, or passerby.
Nothing - I'll be heading to the foundry soon.
Collateral damage is the best way to tie up loose ends. Give me the bomb.
It's liberation.
Even a mountain of magic wouldn't be enough to stop those behemoths. No, there's only one way of stopping the Steel Watch.
Sneak in, place the bomb, sneak out - bang. Seems simple enough.
I'll blow up the foundry - give me the bomb.
We need to stop them, and there's only one way to do it.
Exactly.
You just need a little assistance, and I can provide it.
Yes.
The streets will be clear of Watchers in no time.
They act all civilized... servants of the people. But they only serve one man.
Those metal monsters spit in nature's face, but mass murder is a bit far.
As long as our objective is the same, the reason doesn't matter to me. We have a common enemy.
My way's the only way - I think you're just too delicate to admit it.
I'm convinced - give me the bomb, and I'll take out the foundry.
You can count on me. I'll put a stop to those mechanised horrors.
Personally, I put a lot of the blame on Gortash.
Neither was Moonrise, and look how that turned out. You have a knack for passing among these bastards as if you were one of them.
And yet here you are, all in one piece. Most people who cross them aren't much more than a stain on the street afterwards.
You almost sound convinced by your own rothshit.

EditorData.NodeContext: rothshit = shit of a roth = ROW-thay-shit

Text.Value: Scared or not, you can't take down every Steel Watcher in the city. Unless you hit the people who build them - the Gondians.
Good. I'd wish you luck, but I know you won't need it.
I'll do it.
As long as you see sense, I don't care when you see it.
These Steel Watchers. One of them is the equivalent of a red dragon. An army of them, well... there's never been an army of dragons.
Are you sure this is the only way?
I knew you were the practical sort. That's why we get along.
I've been to the Foundry - the Gondians are prisoners.
Exactly. You freed us from Ketheric's rotten cells - I reckon you can rid us of these Gondians just as easily.
Prisoners can lay down their tools.
So take the bomb. Just in case I'm right, and you're wrong.
Could be they're part of the cult. Could just be for coin. Couldn't possibly tell you.
There's a line where bravery becomes stupidity. You just crossed it.
You can do what's needed - I'm sure of it.
Fine. I'll take it - but I'll only use it as a last resort.
So - are you with me? Ready to take down the Steel Watch?

EditorData.NodeContext: Keen to inspire the player to join his cause

Text.Value: Wulbren, please. This is too far! Everyone in the foundry would be killed.
They would have licked Sarevok's boots given the chance, and now they'll kiss Gortash's ring while the city screams.
The Fist want you dead - I offered to help.
Keep your bomb. I'm doing this my way.
But neither of us gets what we want until we deal with our biggest obstacle.
I've already run foul of the Watchers myself.
I can blame them for precisely that reason.
Careful - lots of open flames down here. Don't want that bomb close to any of them. What is it?

EditorData.NodeContext: Concerned due to the player carrying a highly dangerous explosive

Text.Value: I'm not scared of dragons. Or Steel Watchers.
They invented the Steel Watchers. And they're building an army of them.
Maybe the Gondians are victims, not oppressors.
Leave.
If they had any courage, they'd have refused him and died like heroes, spitting in his face.
Barcus has a point - this sounds like mass murder.
By hitting the Gondians. Hard.
The city's not exactly safe for me either.
And the citizens have rolled out the red carpet for their new tyrant.
Remind me what to do with the bomb.
Good to see you. Wasn't sure you'd make it to the city. Regretting it yet?
Cheer up Wulbren. We're here to help.
I'm not quite an army of dragons, but I'm the closest thing you'll probably find.
Keep your head down, get to the Lower City, and find the foundry down by the docks.
I spent a lot of time thinking of worst case scenarios while I was locked in that cell you plucked me out of at Moonrise.
I had a plan to put a stop to them. But the way things are now, if we stick our heads above ground, the Watchers are on us like flies on shit.
Bloody fool. That bomb was one-of-a-kind - I trusted you with it because you know what's at stake.
EXACTLY.
Innocents. You have no idea what you're talking about.

EditorData.NodeContext: fanatical - "exactly" is said in vindication -  "innocents" said in derision, disguist

Text.Value: A tyrant's nothing without lackeys. And the Gondians are the perfect lackeys. Dangerously intelligent, pathetically submissive.
But their idea of diplomacy is a steel fist shoved where the sun don't shine.
They've always been happy to provide their technology to despots in exchange for a stipend and the freedom to work in peace.
There is no other way.
There must be a reason the Gondians would do something so terrible.
Same as it always is. Eliminate the threat.
These Gondians are not poor, unknowing mages scribbling spell scrolls for Minute Meteors or Acid Arrows. They are complicit.
Good. We don't have a chance unless we stick together - not while the Gondians' metal monsters are patrolling the streets.
I'll make contact with the Gondians - maybe they'll see reason.
The runepowder bomb was our best chance of crushing the Steel Watch, and you squandered it.
Perhaps. All the more reason to get rid of them.
The Fists sent me to crush your resistance. Time to die.
Gortash is the enemy - not the Gondians. I'll find another way.
I still don't buy it. Would you blame a mage for how the spells they wrote are used?
I heard about that. You had the Harpers all excited, but there aren't many Harpers left.
Get the bomb inside the Gondian facility, and - boom. Problem solved.
Why put the blame on the Gondians?
Resistance fighters are few and far between - my Ironhands, what's left of the Harpers, and you. I hope.
This is too messy for me - I'm out.

EditorData.logicalname: Player took the bomb outside of the dialog

Text.Value: Now they'll die like the dogs they are.
How do we stop them?
When he becomes Grand Duke, it will only get worse. Laws will change, freedoms will vanish, and soon you'll be accused and sentenced before you've even committed a crime.
Quiet, Barcus. The adults are talking.
Perhaps the Gondians were infected with a tadpole?
Destroy their factory, for the sake of the city.
I'm with you.
Find another way to take the foundry down, or kiss Baldur's Gate goodbye.
I'll shut down production, but not using your methods.
What was the plan?
I wouldn't have asked you if it wasn't, friend.
I didn't imagine anything as bad as this. The Gondians have handed Enver Gortash the means to bring about the end of liberty in Baldur's Gate.
I'm sure you can.
No plan survives contact with the enemy - unless I'm involved.
I've built something unique for just that purpose.
It's going to be quite the explosion - I can't wait.
In this case - the foundry where these atrocities are produced.

Synopsis: Main Wulbren dialog in gnomes hideout cellar of a smithy in Rivington. Wulbren should give player a quest to destroy Gondian workshop.
